<root>Then, to solve for r, we can isolate our trig functions and use the identity 
  <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
    <semantics>
      <mrow>
        <msup>
          <mi>sin</mi>
          <mn>2</mn>
        </msup>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>cos</mi>
          <mn>2</mn>
        </msup>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mrow>
      <annotation encoding="SnuggleTeX">$\sin^2 + \cos^2 = 1$</annotation>
    </semantics>
  </math> to get to the equation 
  <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
    <semantics>
      <mrow>
        <mfenced close=")" open="(">
          <mrow>
            <mo>-</mo>
            <msup>
              <mfrac>
                <mi>A</mi>
                <mi>r</mi>
              </mfrac>
              <mn>2</mn>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </mfenced>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mfenced close=")" open="(">
          <msup>
            <mfrac>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mi>r</mi>
            </mfrac>
            <mn>2</mn>
          </msup>
        </mfenced>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mrow>
      <annotation encoding="SnuggleTeX">$$(-\frac{A}{r}^2) + (\frac{B}{r}^2) = 1$$</annotation>
    </semantics>
  </math>Using algebra to solve for r, we find that 
  <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
    <semantics>
      <mrow>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <msqrt>
          <mrow>
            <msup>
              <mi>A</mi>
              <mn>2</mn>
            </msup>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <msup>
              <mi>B</mi>
              <mn>2</mn>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
        </msqrt>
      </mrow>
      <annotation encoding="SnuggleTeX">$$r = \sqrt{A^2 + B^2}$$</annotation>
    </semantics>
  </math>
</root>